<br>
Cold, empty space is not quite as cold or empty as many people might think. <br>
<br>
What is often described as a vacuum, the region between stars, is actually mostly filled with gas that can have a temperature of millions of degrees. The material comes from the gas and dust that pervades the universe. The heat probably comes from stellar explosions called supernovae, astronomers say, but because the heating events happen so quickly, they're difficult to observe.<br>
<br>
Therefore, astronomers who study this so-called interstellar medium must watch it cool, and they will soon have a new tool to do that with.  <br>
 On Dec. 19, NASA plans to launch CHIPS, the Cosmic Hot Interstellar Plasma Spectrometer, from Vandenberg Air Force Base. The satellite will study, at much-neglected wavelengths, the under-recognized pocket of hot, glowing gas that enshrouds the space between stars. <br>
<br>
&quot;CHIPS is going to collect the first extreme ultraviolet spectra of truly diffuse emission,&quot; says Mark Hurwitz, the mission's principal investigator from University of California, Berkeley.<br>
<br>
The big picture<br>
<br>
Unlike Hubble and other telescopes that are designed to peer as deep into space and as far back in time as possible, and therefore look at a narrow patch of sky, CHIPS is looking at the big picture. Its field-of-view is 6X25 degrees, where a person's outstretched hand held at arm's length against the sky measures about 20 degrees from pinky to thumb. Hubble, by comparison, has a field-of-view about the size of President Roosevelt's eye on a dime held at arm's length. <br>
<br>
Chips will also take advantage of spectroscopy, not imaging. <br>
<br>
The spectrograph on Chips will capture light from the interstellar medium, separate it, as white light through a prism is spread out, and analyze it. Individual lines that show up in the resulting spectra can reveal characteristics of the material such as composition, density, and pressure. <br>
<br>
&quot;Basically CHIPS sees a great big piece of sky and takes spectra of all that light put together,&quot; Hurwitz says. &quot;And what we hope to see is emission from hot plasma that is believed to fill much of the space surrounding the nearest couple of hundred light-years from the Sun.&quot;<br>
<br>
That hot plasma fills what astronomers call the Local Bubble, which measures about 600 light-years across. It includes many stars yet is but a corner of the Milky Way Galaxy. <br>
<br>
A cool kind of hot<br>
<br>
The gas in the Local Bubble consists mostly of hydrogen and helium at about a million degrees Kelvin, almost 200 times hotter than the surface of the Sun. Yet it doesn't incinerate everything it comes in contact with because it is, as Hurwitz describes it, diffuse, or tenuous. Scoop up a coffee mug of the stuff and there might be one lone atom captured. <br>
<br>
&quot;The amount of radiation that it gives off, and the heat that you might receive as radiation, depends on density,&quot; explains Ed Jenkins, a senior research astronomer at Princeton University.<br>
<br>
The Local Bubble sits in an interstellar medium that is on average 1,000 times more dense. A coffee mug of that stuff would gather about 500 atoms. <br>
<br>
Scientists believe that the Local Bubble was evacuated millions of years ago by a series of supernovae, or violent explosions that massive stars undergo as they die. But they're not sure. <br>
<br>
&quot;We're essentially looking at hot gas that's left over from some historical events,&quot; Hurwitz said. &quot;And it'll be interesting to see, for example, are we in the center of this bubble, is the emission brighter on one side or the other, is there some indication that the gas is cooler on one side or the other? Because that might also tell us a little bit more about what caused it in the first place.&quot;<br>
<br>
Other tasks<br>
<br>
CHIPS data may also help astronomers understand more about other phenomena in the universe. <br>
<br>
First, knowing how plasmas or gases cool will help scientists model how supernovae radiate energy, Hurwitz said. <br>
<br>
And stars and clouds such as the Local Bubble are the building blocks for galaxies. So CHIPS data should help scientists understand galactic-scale phenomena. <br>
<br>
&quot;When you look at a galaxy full of stars, what's really going on is there's a whole ecosystem,&quot; Hurwitz says. &quot;New stars are forming out of clouds of interstellar gas. And some of those will be very massive, and they will then detonate as supernovae, which will then create these hot bubbles of gas and send shock waves out that, in some cases, are believed to then trigger star formation in cold, dense gas that the shock waves encounter. So there's this whole life cycle going on.&quot;<br>
<br>
Galaxies and gas clouds, in turn, pervade the universe. <br>
<br>
&quot;The hot gas fills so much of the universe that a lot of things depend on how much of it there is,&quot; says Bryan Penprase, associate professor of astronomy at Pomona College in California. &quot;This has implications for the whole structure of the universe.&quot;<br>
<br>
Hurwitz's Space Sciences Laboratory at the University of California, Berkeley, teamed with California-based private firm SpaceDev to build CHIPS. While many space satellites can cost hundreds of millions of dollars or more, this mission was built on the cheap, with a $15 million budget cap. <br>
<br>
It is expected to operate for one year. <br>
